# Introduction to Testing Your Code

Testing is how you verify that your code does what you intend — not just once, but every time you change something. Without tests, every edit is a guess.

## Why Testing Matters in C++

C++ gives you a lot of control, which also means a lot of ways to introduce subtle bugs. A function that returns the wrong value, a loop that runs one iteration too many, a pointer that outlives its allocation — none of these produce a compiler error. Tests catch them before users do.

The core idea is simple: call a piece of code with known inputs and check that the output matches your expectation. If it doesn't, the test fails and you know exactly where to look.

## Assertions as the Simplest Test

The most direct testing tool in C++ is `assert` from `<cassert>`. It takes a boolean expression and terminates the program if it evaluates to false. This is useful for quick sanity checks during development.

```cpp
#include <cassert>
#include <string>
#include <format>

int clamp(int value, int lo, int hi) {
    if (value < lo) return lo;
    if (value > hi) return hi;
    return value;
}

int main() {
    assert(clamp(5, 0, 10) == 5);
    assert(clamp(-3, 0, 10) == 0);
    assert(clamp(15, 0, 10) == 10);
    std::println("All tests passed.");
}
```

Each `assert` acts as a mini-test. If `clamp` is broken, the program halts with a message pointing to the failing line.

## Limitations of Raw Assertions

`assert` is stripped out in release builds (when `NDEBUG` is defined), so it cannot serve as a permanent safety net. It also gives minimal output — you get a line number, not a description of what went wrong or what value was actually returned.

For serious projects, dedicated testing frameworks like Catch2 or GoogleTest provide named test cases, descriptive failure messages, and structured output. They let you organise tests separately from production code and run them automatically.

## The Testing Habit

The most valuable thing testing teaches is to write small, focused functions — code that takes inputs and returns outputs without hidden side effects. Such functions are easy to test. Code tangled with global state or I/O is not.

Even informal tests written as `main`-function assertions are far better than no tests at all. Start small, run often, and expand coverage as your programs grow.

