## `std::cin` and Handling Invalid Input

`std::cin` enters a *fail state* when the input doesn't match the expected type — for example, typing `"abc"` when the program expects an `int`. Once in a fail state, all subsequent reads silently do nothing until you explicitly clear it. This is one of the most common sources of mysterious loops and frozen programs.

Two member functions matter most:

- `std::cin.fail()` — returns `true` if the last extraction failed
- `std::cin.clear()` — resets the error flags so reads work again
- `std::cin.ignore(n, delim)` — discards up to `n` characters from the buffer, stopping at `delim`; use `std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max()` with `'\n'` to flush the whole line

Even a *successful* extraction can leave a problem: typing `42\n` extracts `42` but leaves `\n` in the buffer, which a later `std::getline` will swallow immediately. The fix is the same `ignore` call.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <limits>
#include <format>

int getPositiveInt() {
    int value{};
    while (true) {
        std::cout << "Enter a positive integer: ";
        std::cin >> value;
        if (!std::cin.fail() && value > 0)
            return value;
        std::cin.clear();
        std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), '\n');
        std::cout << std::format("Invalid input. Try again.\n");
    }
}
```

The loop retries until both conditions hold: no extraction failure *and* the value is in range. Separating these two checks is deliberate — a failed extraction leaves `value` unchanged from its previous state, so testing `value > 0` alone after a bad read would silently pass on whatever value happened to be there before.

This pattern connects back to **Common Semantic Errors in C++**: relying on an uninitialised or stale variable after a failed read is exactly the kind of silent logic error that produces wrong output with no compiler warning.

Extraction with `>>` also skips leading whitespace by default, which is usually convenient. `std::getline` does *not* skip whitespace, so mixing the two in the same program requires care with the leftover newline described above.

For programs that need robust input handling, consider reading the whole line with `std::getline` first and then parsing or validating the string, which avoids most of the fail-state complexity entirely.

